THE MATHEMATICS GENDER GAP¶

Effects On Student's and Parent's Attitude¶

Considering MATHEMATICS as an OVERALL SCORE¶
INVESTIGATION OVERVIEW¶

In this investigation, I wanted to require a better a glance at what attitudes of both the scholars and fogeys that contributed to overall PISA score's gender gap. the most focus was gender, different sorts of attitudes of scholars towards math (motivation, anxiety, interest, work ethic, behaviour) also because the the student's perception on how their parent's view math.

DATASET OVERVIEW¶

The given PISA 2012 dataset contained information from 485,490 students and 646 features. After the data cleaning process, I condensed the amount of features to 10: country, gender, overall math score, motivation score, anxiety score, interest score, work ethic score, behaviour score, and parent's attitude towards math score. All features under the attitude have a scale of 4 points, marking the highest positive attitude, to 1 point, marking a negative attitude. Anxiety works conversely, where one point shows a student to be less anxious (positive attitude) and 4 points being really anxious towards math with negative attitude.

DISTRIBUTION OF MATH SCORE¶

DISTRIBUTION OF ATTITUDE SCORES OF STUDENTS ON THE BASIS OF GENDER¶

If we take a glance at the distribution of high scores within the category of motivation, interest, behaviour and self, the male students outweight the females students. But if we take a glance at the high scores when it involves anxiety and work ethic, the females students seem to attain above the male students.

GENDER PROPORTION of scholars WITH TOP PERCENTILE¶

We can see clearly here that because the top percentile increases, so does the gender gap. Initially, the feminine proportion was higher (due to the very fact that there was a rather more female students taking the survey as compared to the male students). But by the time we arrived to the highest (approximately) 20th percentile, the quantity of female students was adequate to the quantity of male students. All throughout the rise of top percentiles, we see that the proportion of male students strictly increases also . Notice that the further we get along the highest percentile of scholars , the gender gap's increase accelerates.

seaborn.lineplot(data=data,x='nth_percentile',y='f_prop', label='Female')

plt.legend()
plt.title('GENDER PROPORTION OF STUDENTS WITH TOP PERCENTILE')##title
plt.ylabel('proportion')##ylabel
plt.xlabel('nth percentile of overall math score');##xlabel
